# A js`…@{}…` embedded-hole attribute on a ≥2-spread element folds through
# composeBag, which cannot yet lower a js/css hole into the shared bag (each
# @{ } hole needs JS/CSS-context escaping into the bag value — a security-
# careful, separate feature). This is a NON-regression gap: a js/css hole on a
# ≥2-spread element was always an error. Part C makes the diagnostic accurate
# for the element-fold context — it no longer claims the attribute "cannot be
# used as a component prop" (there is no component here).
-- input.gsx --
package views

import "github.com/gsxhq/gsx"

component JSCssHoleTwoSpreads(u string, p gsx.Attrs, q gsx.Attrs) {
	<button { p... } onclick=js"do(@{u})" { q... }>go</button>
}
-- diagnostics.golden --
6:19: embedded js attribute literal "onclick" with @{ } interpolation is not yet supported on an element that merges its attributes (<button>); each @{ } hole needs js-context escaping into the shared bag, which is not yet ported
